titleproper.value:
Guide to the Daniel French Papers
                    <num>WAG.101</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Jane Latour, c.1997 and Wendy Scheir, 2005.

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2012-03-29T21:12-0400</date>

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: Daniel French (1908-1996) joined the International Brotherhood of Painters and Allied Trades (IBPAT) in 1934, and was elected as a delegate from his local to IBPAT District Council 9 (DC 9) in 1939. In 1946, after three years fighting in World War II, French was elected Business Agent of his local, and was reelected to the post for the next five terms. In 1953, French joined IBPAT Local 490. As President of Local 490, French charged certain DC 9 officials with corruption, and became involved in a series of lengthy legal battles. The collection documents Frenchâ€™s five decades of struggle against union corruption.

                    <item>Hall, Burton H., editor. 
                        <title render="italic">Autocracy and Insurgency in Organized Labor</title>. New Brunswick: Transaction Books, 1972.</item>
                    <item>
                        <title render="italic">Corruption and Racketeering in the New York City Construction Industry</title>. Interim Report by the New York State Organized Crime Task Force. Ithaca: ILR Press, 1988.</item>
                    <item>
                        <title render="italic">Corruption and Racketeering in the New York City Construction Industry</title>. Final Report to Governor Mario Cuomo. Ronald Goldstock, Director, New York State Organized Crime Task Force. December, 1989.</item>
                    <item>Hutchinson, John. 
                        <title render="italic">The Imperfect Union: A History of Corruption in American Trade Unions</title>. New York: E.P. Dutton, 1972.</item>
                    <item>Zausner, Philip. 
                        <title render="italic">Unvarnished: The Autobiography of a Labor Leader</title>. New York: Brotherhood Publishers, 1941.</item>
                </list>

<emph render="bold">Series II, Biographical Material and Memorabilia</emph>, contains French's campaign materials, including palm cards, flyers, and appeals; identification documents, certifications, and membership materials; documents relating to Ralph French; commemorative publications; and notes.
